<DESC><p style="text-align: center;">REQUEST FOR INFORMATION <br />NAVY SUPPORT MANAGEMENT BRANCH</p>
<p>1.0 Description</p>
<p>1.1 United States Marine Corps (USMC), Blount Island Command (BIC), Jacksonville FL, Contracts Support Management Office (CSMO) in support of Navy Support Management Branch (NSMB) is seeking information on how an interested contractor could perform both OCONUS Navy watercraft preventive maintenance and OCONUS Navy watercraft corrective maintenance/repairs on Navy watercraft embarked on the Maritime Prepositioning Force (MPF) ships.</p>
<p>1.2 THIS IS A REQUEST FOR INFORMATION (RFI) ONLY. This RFI is issued solely for information and planning purposes - it does not constitute a Request for Quote (RFQ) or a promise to issue an RFQ in the future. This request for information does not commit the Government to contract for any supply or service whatsoever. Further, BIC CSMO is not at this time seeking quotes and will not accept unsolicited quotes. Responders are advised that the U.S. Government will not pay for any information or administrative costs incurred in response to this RFI; all costs associated with responding to this RFI will be solely at the interested party's expense. Not responding to this RFI does not preclude participation in any future RFQ, if any is issued. If a solicitation is released, it will be synopsized on the Federal Business Opportunities (FedBizOpps) website WWW.FBO.GOV. It is the responsibility of the potential offerors to monitor this site for additional information pertaining to this requirement. The information provided may be considered, as market research, in making decisions related to socio-economic set-aside of the service requirements described herein.</p>
<p>The Navy Watercraft Afloat Maintenance Services (NWAMS) contract will be an indefinite-delivery-indefinite-quantity type contract with task orders issued annually for preventive maintenance, corrective maintenance and other support.</p>
<p>2.0 Background</p>
<p>The NAVFAC Expeditionary Programs Office (NEPO), Sealift Support Office is responsible for Navy equipment assigned to the Maritime Prepositioned Force (MPF). The MPF consists of forward deployed ships in Guam, Diego Garcia, and Saipan carrying NEPO equipment. NEPO's equipment is used in training exercises and contingencies and which must remain operationally ready. This requires timely maintenance and repairs of Navy watercraft staged onboard the MPF ships positioned OCONUS. The Navy Branch at BICmd executes maintenance and logistical oversight of NEPO equipment.</p>
<p>MPF Maintenance Cycles (MMCs) have historically occurred in a 36-40 month cycle. After a newly loaded ship departs Blount Island Command (BIC), Florida, it will stay in its assigned theater for approximately 34 to 36 months before returning to BIC to offload for a scheduled shipyard availability.</p>
<p>The MPF currently consists of Marine Prepositioning Squadron (MPS) Squadron Two, located at Diego Garcia; and MPS Squadron Three, in the Guam/Saipan area. These MPF squadrons together consist of ten prepositioned ships configured to transport supplies for the U.S. Marine Corps.</p>
<p>Equipment requiring maintenance and repair is stored on the weather decks of deployed MPF ships. These subject systems are the Improved Navy Lighterage System (INLS), Amphibious Bulk Liquid Transfer System (ABLTS), Landing Craft Mechanized (LCM-8s), and Maritime Prepositioning Force Utility Boat (MPFUBs). The Lighter, Amphibious, Resupply Cargo (LARC) is staged in the interior of the assigned MPS.</p>
<p>Every three years, MPF ships return to the Continental United States for major maintenance and supply refreshment. This cycle is called the MPF Maintenance Cycle (MC) and is held at the Blount Island Command (BIC).</p>
<p>The Navy watercraft are staged onboard the MPS for use by the Naval Beach Groups (NBGs) One and Two (located in Coronado, CA and Little Creek, VA respectively) In Support Of (ISO) exercises and contingencies. The contractor maintains custody and performs maintenance of ABLTS, INLS, LCM-8s, LARC and MPF UBs onboard the ship while the equipment is not under the operational control of the NBGs, which is the majority of time. They will assist with periodic inspections and will manage custody transfer of the equipment, when directed. Between the two MPS squadrons, there are 12 ships. Ten of the twelve MPS currently have Navy watercraft assigned and embarked except during rotation through BIC for the MMC.</p>
<p>The projected watercraft assignments per ship is listed below (Warping Tugs (WT), Causeway Ferries (CF), and Roll-On/Roll-Off Discharge Facility (RRDF) are INLS components, described further below)</p>
<p>*MPS Two (located in Diego Garcia):<br />-USNS Button: 1xWT, 2xCF, 1xMPFUB and 1xABLTS.<br />-USNS Lopez: 1xWT, 3xCF, 1xMPFUB and 1xABLTS.<br />-<br />-USNS Seay: 1xWT, 3xCF, 1xLCM8, 2xLARC and 2xMPF UB.<br />-USNS Sisler: 1xWT, 3xCF and 1xMPFUB.<br />-USNS Williams: 1xWT, 1xRRDF, 1xLCM8, 1xMPFUB, 2xLARC and 1xABLTS.</p>
<p>*MPS Three (located in Guam/Saipan):<br />-USNS Lummus: 1xWT, 2xCF, 1xMPFUB and 1xABLTS.<br />-USNS Stockham: 1xWT, 3xCF, 1xLCM8 and 1xMPFUB.<br />-USNS Bobo: 1xWT, 1xRRDF, 1xLCM8, 1xMPFUB, 2xLARC and 1xABLTS.<br />-USNS Dahl: 1xWT, 3xCF and 1xMPFUB.<br />-USNS Pililaau: 1xWT, 3xCF, 1xLCM8, 2xLARC and 2xMPFUB.</p>
<p>The following paragraphs describe the equipment and systems that require maintenance.</p>
<p>Amphibious Bulk Liquid Transfer System (ABLTS)<br />ABLTS is a reel-laid buoyant hose system for fuel or water transfer. The system has a total of three hose reels. Two of the reels are capable of deploying 5,000 feet of 6-inch fuel hose. The third hose reel has 10,000 feet of 4-inch potable water hose.</p>
<p>Improved Navy Lighterage System (INLS)<br />The INLS is a system of steel modules that are interconnected by rigid and flexible connections. These modules are used to construct causeway ferries and Roll-On/Roll-Off Discharge Facilities for the loading and unloading of material from ships to shore. The individual non-powered modules are nominally 80' long, 24' wide, and 8' deep. The individual modules can be assembled to form specific platforms. The 3 INLS platforms assigned to MPF are:<br />&bull; Warping Tug (WT)<br />&bull; Causeway Ferry (CF)<br />o Consists of the Causeway Ferry Power Module (CFPM, Intermediate Module (IM) and Beach Module (BM)<br />&bull; Roll-On/Roll-Of Discharge Facility (RRDF)<br />o A system of 9 non-powered modules including 7 Combination Modules (CM), 1 Docking Module (DM) and 1 Ramp Module (RM); also included are side connectors to attach them together and a Containerized Crew Shelter (CCS)<br />Listed below are the major individual components that make up INLS:</p>
<p>Warping Tug<br />The Warping Tug (WT) is a single powered module used to assist and support other INLS platforms and operations. The WT operates independent of all other modules. It assists in platform assembly, disassembly, ABLTS installation, anchor deployment and retrieval, salvage, towing, station keeping and other tasks in support of a full range of operations. WTs are 87'9" long, 24' wide, 8' deep and weigh approximately 111 Long Tons (LT) as loaded on the MPF ships (with 25% fuel onboard).</p>
<p>Causeway Ferry Power Module<br />The Causeway Ferry Power Module (CFPM) is one of the modules that make up the Causeway Ferry (CF) platform. The CFPM provides primary propulsion and control for the Causeway Ferry which is assembled using one CFPM, one Intermediate Module (IM) and 1 Beach Module (BM). In addition to propulsion and control, the CFPM provides the stern drive through capability, cargo deck space, along with the other CF modules, for loading, securing and transportation of cargo. CFPMs are 87'7" long, 24' wide, 8' deep and weigh approximately 107 LT as loaded on the MPF ships (with 25% fuel onboard).</p>
<p>Intermediate Module<br />The Intermediate Module (IM) is a non-powered module that is used in the assembly of the CF. The IM has flexor connectors fore and aft so that it can be connected with other modules end to end. IMs are 80' long, 24' wide, 8' deep, and weigh approximately 69 LT.</p>
<p>Beach Module<br />The Beach Module (BM) is one of two powered modules that together with an IM make up the CF. The BM bow thruster provides assisted maneuvering of the CF. and is controlled wirelessly from the CFPM. In addition to the bow thruster, the BM provides a hydraulically operated ramp to enable drive-on or drive-off capabilities for the rolling cargo to the beach. BMs are 89'10.75" long, 24' wide, 8' deep and weigh approximately 90 LT as loaded on the MPF ships (with 25% fuel onboard).</p>
<p>Combination Module<br />The Combination Module (CM) is a non-powered module. The CM is the primary module making of the RRDF platform (7 CMs are used). The CM has flexor connectors fore and aft so that it can be connected with other CMs, IMs, RMs, or DMs end to end. In addition, the CM has side connector pockets so that it can be connected side to side with other CMs and DMs using hydraulically operated side connectors. The side connectors are positioned in the female housings on each side of the CM and activated (locked) hydraulically. CMs are 80' long, 24' wide, 8' deep, and weigh approximately 77 LT without side connectors.</p>
<p>Docking Module<br />The Docking Module (DM) is similar to the CM in dimensions, with the addition of a fixed angle ramp on one end. The DM is provided with female side connector recesses that are configured identically to the side connector recesses of the CM. Like the CM, the housings are used for rigid attachment to other CMs comprising a RRDF. The end of the DM that mates with the CFPM has a roadway that slopes to meet the deck of the CFPM and connects to the CFPM by means of the Flexible Connector System. The connection system is designed to provide a secure engagement during vehicle transfer operations. DMs are 80' long, 24' wide, 8' deep, and weigh approximately 78 LT.</p>
<p>Ramp Module<br />The Ramp Module (RM) is a non-powered module that is used in the assembly of the RRDF. The RM facilitates the loading and unloading of other displacement landing craft/Lighterage such as the Landing Craft Mechanized (LCM8), Landing Craft and Utility (LCU). RMs are 80' long, 24' wide, 8' deep, and weigh approximately 62 LT.</p>
<p>Containerized Crew Shelter<br />The Containerized Crew Shelter (CCS) provides habitability, communication, and stowage for personnel assigned to the RRDF. It is provided with a Heating, Ventilation, and Air Conditioning (HVAC) system that maintain the interior habitability at 60oF to 85oF. The CCS is divided into three primary spaces. The diesel generator space and the Hydraulic Power Unit (HPU)/storage space share one end of the container and are separated by an inner wall. These two spaces occupy approximately one third of the 20 foot container. The crew room occupies the rest of the container. The CCS weighs approximately 15 LT.</p>
<p>Side Connector<br />The INLS Side Connector (SC) System consists of two major assemblies - the Male-to-Male Connector and the Remote Control Station Cart Assembly. The main purpose of the connector is to provide a means of side connecting the INLS CMs to form a rigid connection in the assembly of larger platforms. SCs are also used to connect a DM with a CM. The connectors mate with female pockets located on the side of each CM/DM. The individual connectors are installed in three of the seven CMs per RRDF and the Remote Cart is installed in the CCS. Side Connectors weigh 4200 pounds each.</p>
<p>Landing Craft, Mechanized (LCM-8)<br />LCM-8s have been in the fleet since 1959 transporting cargo, troops and vehicles between ships and shore and also performing lighter and utility work in harbors. The LCM-8 is designed for use in rough or exposed waters and can be operated through breakers and grounded on the beach. The hydraulically operated bow ramp allows RORO operations with wheeled and tracked vehicles. LCM-8s are 73'7" long, 21'1" wide, have a draft of 4'7" and weigh approximately 75 LT.</p>
<p>Maritime Prepositioning Force Utility Boat (MPF UB)<br />MPFUBs were designed to transfer personnel and their associated equipment (30 people with 150 lbs. of equipment each), cargo (10,000 lbs.), and waterborne medical evacuations between ships and shore as well as provide protection and security in the area of operations. MPFUBs are 41'1" long, 14'6" wide, have a draft of 2'6" and weigh approximately 11 LT.</p>
<p>2.1 Compliance Requirements</p>
<p>The Contractor will be required to comply with all U.S. and international law. This includes but is not limited to, international trade, customs, labor, and environmental laws, for all personnel and operations.</p>
<p>3.0 Scope</p>
<p>This requirement is needed to execute OCONUS Navy Watercraft Afloat Maintenance Services ISO the US Marine Corps Maritime Prepositioning Force Program. The Contractor's Program Manager will be responsible for overall management of the contract. The Program Manager shall be the single point of contact for all matters pertaining to the performance of the contract and will be the Program Manager's primary duty.</p>
<p>This requirement includes support services in the following two service areas:</p>
<p>Service Area I - Afloat Preventive Maintenance and associated logistics support. This service area is critical to ensuring that the Navy Watercraft remain full mission capable. The tasks within this service area provide continuous OCONUS Preventive Maintenance (PM) IAW a Government provided Maintenance Requirements Package (MRP), which details maintenance tasks and periodicities. PM is performed in the afloat environment on Navy watercraft stage onboard MPF ships with performance of preventive maintenance subject to MPS schedule and MPS crew activities. PM is not performed during the MPS rotation through BICmd. PM will require dedicated employees for each MPS that are responsible for and maintain custody of the assigned Navy watercraft. PM will also require dedicated employees with specific skill sets be assigned to each squadron to support all MPS in that squadron. The Contractor employees work and live onboard the MPS.</p>
<p>This includes, but is not limited to, the following Navy watercraft: Maritime Prepositioning Force Utility Boat (MPFUB), Lighter, Amphibious, Resupply Cargo (LARC), Landing Craft Mechanized-8 (LCM-8), ABLTS and Improved Navy Lighterage System (INLS), which includes: Warping Tug (WT), Causeway Ferry Power Module, Causeway Ferry Beach Module, Causeway Ferry Intermediate Module and the Roll On/Roll Off Discharge Facility (RRDF) system which includes the Docking Module, Ramp Module and Combination Module, Containerized Crew Shelter (CCS) and RRDF Side Connector system (SC) staged on MPF shipping, deployed overseas. The MRP Standard Work Items (SWI) tasks consist of preventive maintenance for the INLS, LCM-8, MPF UB and ABLTS systems once they are placed aboard the MPF Ships. Type of maintenance includes specific maritime disciplines such as electrical, mechanical, electronic, corrosion control and boat equipage. This service area does not include CONUS based maintenance services as these services are performed under a different BICmd contract.</p>
<p>Service Area II - Afloat Corrective Maintenance and associated logistics support. This service area is critical to ensuring that the Navy Watercraft are full mission capable. The repair work required is normally unscheduled/unknown but is continuous and ongoing as a result of a robust exercise schedule and is contingent upon the following factors: watercraft access and availability, weather, mission, exercise schedule, and shipboard activities. Examples of scheduling challenges are ship movement from homeport for ship crew proficiency training, Military Sealift Command (MSC) controlled. Ship movement in support of MPF exercises, Combatant Command (COCOM) controlled. Ship movement for inclement weather sortie, MSC controlled and ship crew performing various ship maintenance or preservation operations that may impede the contractor from simultaneously working on the embarked watercraft. The items listed above all have priority over lighterage maintenance, which severely restricts the Prime Contractor's window of opportunity to perform needed repairs. This is further exasperated when the lighterage onboard receives damage during an exercise as it significantly increases the workload in an already restricted window.</p>
<p>The tasks within this service area provide OCONUS Intermediate and Depot Level Repair and associated logistic support services. Maintenance requirements for this service area normally result from exercise damage or "growth" work from preventive maintenance covered in Service area I above. Some repairs may be emergent in nature, requiring immediate repair. Routine repairs in the afloat environment are subject to MPF shipping schedules. This includes, but is not limited to, the following Navy watercraft: Maritime Prepositioning Force Utility Boat (MPFUB), Lighter, Amphibious, Resupply Cargo (LARC), Landing Craft Mechanized-8 (LCM-8), ABLTS and Improved Navy Lighterage System (INLS), which includes: Warping Tug (WT), Causeway Ferry Power Module, Causeway Ferry Beach Module, Causeway Ferry Intermediate Module and the Roll On/Roll Off Discharge Facility (RRDF) system which includes the Docking Module, Ramp Module and Combination Module, Containerized Crew Shelter (CCS) and RRDF Side Connector system (SC) staged on MPF shipping, deployed overseas. The tasks consist of corrective maintenance and repair of the INLS, LCM-8, MPF UB, LCM8 and ABLTS systems once they are placed aboard the MPF Ships. Type of work includes various ship repair disciplines, but not limited to, hull cleaning, , minor steel fabrication, shipfitter, welding, mechanical, machining, piping, hydraulics, electrical, electronic, selective paint surface conditioning, selective coating systems (painting/non skidding). Depending on the severity of damage, depot level repair may require watercraft removal from the ship for OCONUS dry docking. It may also include priority short notice selective repairs or upgrades to Navy watercraft. This service area does not include CONUS based maintenance services as these services are performed under a different BICmd contract.</p>
<p>4.0 Requested Information</p>
<p>4.1 Interested parties are requested to respond to this RFI with a Capabilities Statement.</p>
<p>4.2 Capability Statements must be submitted NO LATER THAN 05 November, 2018 4:00 EST. Responses shall be submitted via e-mail to stanley.sanders@bic.usmc.mil and patricia.solberg@bic.usmc.mil . Proprietary information, if any, should be minimized and MUST BE CLEARLY MARKED. To aid the Government, please segregate proprietary information. There is no page limitation for submission. Please be advised that all submissions become Government property and will not be returned.</p>
<p>4.3 Section 1 of the Capability Statement shall provide administrative information, and shall include the following as a minimum:</p>
<p>4.3.1 Name, mailing address, phone number, fax number, and e-mail of designated point of contact.</p>
<p>4.3.2 DUNS and CAGE code from System for Award Management (SAM) registration. If your company is not registered in SAM you may still provide a response to this RFI. Be advised should your company wish to compete for any future work. SAM registration will be required prior to submitting a quote. For more information please visit the following link: https://www.sam.gov.</p>
<p>4.3.3. Business type (large business, small business, small disadvantaged business, 8(a)-certified small disadvantaged business, HUB Zone small business, woman-owned small business, very small business, veteran-owned small business, service-disabled veteran-owned small business) based upon North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code 811310 as the work to be performed that is for commercial and industrial machinery (except automotive and electronic) repair and maintenance or 336611 Ship Building and Repairing. "Small business concern" means a concern, including its affiliates, which is independently owned and operated, not dominant in the field of operation in which it is bidding on Government contracts, and qualified as a small business under the criteria and size standards in 13 CFR part 121. Please refer to Federal Acquisition Regulation FAR 19 for additional detailed information on Small Business Size Standards. The FAR is available at https://www.acquisition.gov and http://farsite.hill.af.mil.</p>
<p>4.3.4 Identify subcontractor support which would be required to provide capabilities to perform the services required in one or more of the service areas identified above. All critical subcontractors must be identified, to include DUNS/CAGE information and Business type as described above.</p>
<p>4.4 Section 2 of the Capabilities Statement shall provide a detailed description of the capabilities to perform the services as described in Services Area(s) 1 and 2 above; the Capability Statement must address each Service Area separately. Section 2 shall clearly describe if your Company can perform only Service Area 1, Service Area 2 or both. Describe the physical security of the facilities in which the required services can be performed; this description must include watercraft moored to piers or dry-docked. A description of capabilities must include a discussion as to whether the facilities to perform required services would be dedicated and how the area(s) would be segregated (disassembly area, blast &amp; paint shop, machine shop, weld shop, testing area). In addition, capabilities statements must include a discussion of the capability to transport the corresponding equipment in each Service Area.</p>
<p>5.0 Questions</p>
<p>Questions regarding this announcement shall be submitted in writing by e-mail to the Contract Specialist with CC to the Contracting Officer, email address. Verbal questions will NOT be accepted. Questions will be answered by posting answers to this RFI as additional information. The Government does not guarantee that questions received after 28 October, 2018 4:00 EST will be answered.</p>
<p>6.0 Summary</p>
<p>THIS IS A REQUEST FOR INFORMATION (RFI) ONLY to identify sources that can perform afloat navy craft repairs and various types of navy craft repairs. The information provided in the RFI is subject to change and is not binding on the Government. The Navy has not made a commitment to procure any of the items discussed, and release of this RFI should not be construed as such a commitment or as authorization to incur cost for which reimbursement would be required or sought. All submissions become Government property and will not be returned.</p>
